Bank Marketing

The dataset is from marketing campaigns (phone calls) of Portuguese banking institution inviting clients to subscribe to a product service (bank term deposit). The answers are either a 'yes' or 'no' from customers. Some clients were contacted twice in order to access if they will subscribe. The dataset is from UCI dataset repository

The goal of this dataset and classification is to predict if a client will subscribe (yes) or not (no) to the term deposit (y variable)

summary
  1. The first obvious information from the EDA is that percentage of success (yes response) from the marketing campaign is relatively of low percentage to the total contacts made by the bank. Therefore the overall distribution of the data is highly skewed to the right.
  2. There are a number of possible outliers in the numerical variables based on the violin plots and these shall be investigated
  3. The age distribution of most contacts made are between 25 to 60 years which fall under the age of working population.
  4. An important thing to note about the duration of the call is that this feature can have a direct determination on the target (y) because a duration of 0 seconds will automatically mean a no outcome. However, there is no way of knowing the duration of a call and the outcome until the call has been made. So this data will only be available after y has been determined. Therefore this feature will not be taken forward for modelling.
  5. On the categorical features, one of the things that stood out was that most contacts are made via cellular phone more than telephone which reflects the most common present means of communication
  6. Also, you would see that there is a significant increase in the number of contacts made between May and August. This period is the summer period and then there is another sharp rise in November which reflects the month before the end of the year when companies also try the last push to meet their targets. There is minial contact made in December.
  7. Finally, there are some columns with missing data as shown from the heatmap plot with 'poutcome' column having the most missing data among all other features.

Understanding campaign column

The column describes the number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
For reference, the dataset is a marketing campaigns made by the bank to clients through phone calls.

Based on column description, it is NOT number of campaigns made by the bank rather number of contacts made to this client including the last contact (described by previous column). So then a single bank marketing campaign could last from 1 day to several months and all that data account for one bank campaign. It therefore means there could be many contacts made during the period of a single campaign.

Understanding the Pdays values

This column describes the number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; -1 means client was not previously contacted). One thing to know is that each campaign may have lasted several days or months. Therefore in interpreting this column, it will be good to reference that previous column (number of contacts made before this campaign). The number of contact in previous column must at least be 1.

Looking at the row with 275 previous contact, it looks like something is wrong. The numbers say the duration of present call was 349 seconds, no of present contacts (campaign) is 2, number of pdays passed 262. if only 2 contacts are made presently, it means the frequency of contact is low. And there has been 262 (almost 9 months) since last contact and the poutcome was other. assumning a client is contacted once per day during a campaign period, 275 contacts means the client was contact every single working day of the year. That's impossible. Additionaly, if you look at the distribution of campaign( which outlines the number of contacts made in present campaign) the maximum value recorded was 63. Therefore previous contact and present contact should fall within the same range

This value is an outlier. Given that this row belongs to the highest class (no) in the target column, and the mean and median of the previous columm is zero, but this row ahs pdays >-1, i will drop the row.

Now that all the suspected outlier columns have been inspected, i will inspect the entire dataset for valid entries based on information about the data.

Dataset validation

  1. Because duration column has direct impact on target with zero duration expected to be 'no' target, this shall be confirmed as true.
  2. If previous outcome was success, then why should y target be no. And if previous outcome (poutcome) was yes, why was another contact made? The dataset made no mention of clients canceling their subscriptions during the campaign contacts. If the second condition holds in both ways, it therefore means that previous outcome (poutcome) does not mean that clients have subscribed outrightly for the service. It may only mean that the clients expressed the willingness to subscribe and therefore eventually subscribed or declined on another contact/campaign.
  3. To test for the condition 2 above, I will check that for wherever there is a successful previous outcome (poutcome) that there was a previous contact made (previous > 0)
  4. Finally condition 4 follows from condition three that if the previous outcome is 'other', 'failure', or 'success', there must have been a previous contact. Otherwise poutcome should be 'nan'

There are four columns with empty rows: job, education, contact and poutcome. These are all categorical columns


The job, education and contact column are columns that we cannot make judgement on what they should be based on the rest of the information from the column. They are unique to individual identity profile and as such they are independent of the rest of the data in the columns.


Then for the poutcome column, it was verified in the cells above that all the categorical values in the column except for nan, were clients who had been contacted previously. It therefore means that nan in poutcome simply means that the client has not been contacted. However in this column we have three other categories: other, failure and success.  It may seem that failure and other are the same thing but it isn't. Also, nan and failure or other are not the same. This is because when making a decision to contact a client, these values are in the record of the client and play a role in how the service is presented to the client.  If we wish to model a data where we have no previous knowledge of what the client outcome would be, then all data with previous contact should be dropped. But then there is a problem with this strategy. This is because the campaign column describes the number of contacts made to the client during this campaign. It would mean that any contact greater than 1 will be dropped because if more than a single contact was made, it is likely that the first was a failure (although this can't be verified). Also, the campaign, pdays, previous, month, poutcome, day_of_week willl be redundant as they will add no value to the dataset.  To clean this column, I will rename all nan with zero previous outcome with another categorical word: nil


Then for job, education and contact columns which are independent, i will fill these up with the most frequent values in the columns

dropping duration and campaign column
Duration is the length of the last contact in seconds. This cannot be known until the outcome is determined. By the end of the call, the result is yes or no.

Campaign column describes the number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact).  This modeling wants to predict what the outcome will be for a potential client possibly before launching another marketing campaign.  Therefore, data about the number of contacts made in the present marketing campaign would not be available during the campaign planning. Fog avoidance of leakage, i will drop the campaign column also.

Modelling
In modelling the data, it is important to bear these business objectives: It is important that we identify all positive response clients and so Recall for the positive class is very important. This is because:


    

  1. False negative (missing a willing subscriber) = lost revenue opportunity
    2. 

  2. False positive (calling an unwilling client ) = waste of company resources/time - customer disturbance/annoyance
    3. 



For the modeling of the data, I will employ three approaches with gridsearch to the model considering the class imbalance of the positive label.


    

  1. Sklearn estimators using class weight. The following classifiers will be used model the data using the class weight of sklearn: logistic regression, sgdclassifier, knnclassifier and votingclassifier
    2. 

  2. Combining sklearn with SMOTE from Imbalance to account for the class imbalance
    3. 

  3. finally lightGBM for the data classification
    4. 



For the evaluation: I will employ the following


    

  1. ROC_AUC scores
    2. 

  2. Precision-recall curves
    3. 

  3. confusion matrix and confusion matrix display
    4. 



Finally I will employ cross validation on the best performing model

In[69]:






def gridsearch_results(model, scores : list) -> dict:
    results = {key:np.round(model.cv_results_[key].mean(), 3)
               for key in model.cv_results_.keys()
               if key in scores}
    return results

models = {'Logistic regression': best_lr_model, 
          'SGDClassifier': best_sgd_model, 
          'KNeighborsClassifier': best_kn_model, 
          'VotingClassifier':vote
         }


def plot_confusion_matrix(models: dict, X, y, target_precision=0.3, figsize=(8,7), title='', plot=True) -> dict :

    models_metric = {}

    #figure set up
    if plot:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=figsize, layout='constrained')
        plt.suptitle(f'{title} Confusion Matrix')
        pos = 0
   
    #Compute threshold and predict X_test
    for name, model in models.items(): 
        y_scores = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]
        precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y, y_scores)
        idx = np.where(precision >= target_precision)[0][0]
        threshold_30p = thresholds[idx]
        y_pred_threshold = (y_scores >= threshold_30p).astype(int)

        ## Metric scores
        summary = {}
        summary['AUC'] = (roc_auc_score(y, y_scores)).round(3)
        summary['Average_precision'] = (average_precision_score(y, y_scores)).round(3)
        summary['recall'] = np.round(recall_score(y, y_pred_threshold), 3)
        summary['fi_score'] = np.round(f1_score(y, y_pred_threshold), 3)
        summary['precision_score'] = np.round(precision_score(y, y_pred_threshold), 3)
        ## update dictionary
        models_metric[name] = summary

        ## plotting
        if plot:
            ax = plt.subplot(2, 2, pos+1)
            ax = ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y, y_pred_threshold,
                                                 display_labels=['no', 'yes'],
                                                 colorbar=False, ax=ax)
            ax.ax_.set_title(f'{name}')
            ax.ax_.grid(False)
            # ax.ax_.xaxis.label.set_size(10)
            # ax.ax_.yaxis.get_label().set_fontsize(10)
            ax.ax_.set_ylabel('True label', fontsize=10)
            ax.ax_.set_xlabel('Predicted label\n', fontsize=9)
            pos+=1

    plt.show()

    return models_metric


Class_weight_model = plot_confusion_matrix(models, X_test, y_test, title='Class Weight')

Summary of Model with no class balancing
ROC-AUC Scores: The plot of ROC-AUC curves for the four models used shows that the best performing model is the VotingClassifier with 0.74 AUC score while the poorest is KNeighborsClassifier with AUC score 0.69.  However, because the positive label in the class is low, the models performance are also compared by PR-AUC curve.


Precision-Recall Curve:  The precision recall curve for the four models reveal low precision at high recall. Due to the objective of the model, a high recall will be more beneficial to the model because it will be good to find all clients who are interested in subscribing to the term deposit. At low recall, all the models have high precision and as recall increases, the model that is able to maintain higher precision is the voting classifier.  Kneeighborsclassifier easily loses precision early and becomes week in distinguishing positives from negatives.  Howver, as recall gets to 0.5, all the model collapse to very low precision and labels many samples positive. On the other hand though, given that only 11.7% of the entire dataset is positive, a random guess will give a precision and recall of only 0.117. Comparing this number to the classifier, it shows the model is learning the pattern with voting classifier 3x better than random guess.


Confusion Matrix: The confusion matrix displays the table of results of the predicted X_test using the threshold of 0.3. Overall, the models struggle to predict the positive class as already indicated by the precision_recall curve. For a subscription marketing to client, we can be more confident in the results of the predicted positive classes which are three times better than a random guess.


Finally, the summary metrics for all models reveal that the VotingClassifier outperformed all other models in all metrics

Conclusion
In this notebook, I have taken a bank marketing campaign data for term deposit subscription and modelled potential client responses.  The data was an inbalance dataset showing that only about 11% of the total clients contacted responded positively to the subscription service.


In the modelling, i have compared three different levels of modelling. First was the sklearn class_weight estimators without oversampling of the positive class and relying on the class weight parameter. The second was over_sampling with SMOTE and modelling with Sklearn estimators. The last was using LightGBM classifier to model the data. The models performances were compared and evaluated using ROC-AUC scores, Precision-Recall scores and confusion matrix display. All models struggled to predict the positive classes with varying scores.  The best performing models were cross validated and results showed that the models were able to learn the patterns in the data.


Overall, it was found that the best performing model with higher AUC score, Average precision score, recall, f1_score and accuracy was the LGBMClassifier.
